humour and mutual respect amongst the commissioners despite the tensions over language within the group – and across the country.Scott was a champion of English-language rights in Quebec. Never before published, these diaries provide remarkable insight into the inner life of one of twentieth-century Canada’s most significant intellectuals, and a royal commission that shaped the nation’s language policy for decades to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aBiculturalismzCanada. 0aBilingualismzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Intergovernmental Organizations.2bisacsh  aF R Scott.  aJean March.  aLaurendeau-Dunton.  aLester Pearson.  aQuebec nationalism.  aRoyal Commission.  abiculturalism.  abilingualism.  alanguage crisis.  anational unity crisis.  are Laurendeau.1 aFraser, Graham, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aScott, F.R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311127221408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021z978311127464540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780228009412?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780228009412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780228009412/original  a978-3-11-127221-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  a978-3-11-127464-5  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles